CRIMEAN-CONGO HEMORRHAGIC FEVER - SPAIN: (CASTILE AND LEON) FATAL
*****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: 9 Aug 2018
Source: Sergio E Rodriguez <seerodri@utmb.edu> [edited]


A 74 year old man from Avila, Spain has died from Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever virus (CCHFV). He had been taking part in a hunting activity near the Badajoz town of Helechosa de los Montes, Spain.

In Spain, CCHFV was first detected in hyalomma ticks from Caceres in 2010 and again in 2014 (Estrada-Pena et al, 2012; Cajimat et al, 2017). Subsequently, 2 autochthonous CCHFV cases were reported in August 2016, which resulted in the death of a 62 year old man that in turn resulted in a nosocomial transmission to a 52 year old nurse who was part of the patient's care team (Negredo et al, 2017).

Because the hyalomma tick populations are widely distributed in the Mediterranean basin (Pena Estrada et al, 2004), surveillance for the presence of CCHFV in western Europe is of utmost importance, and these additional cases of CCHFV highlight the growing threat of this disease to the European continent.

References
Estrada-Pena A, Palomar AM, Santibanez P, et al. Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever virus in ticks, southwestern Europe, 2010. Emerg Infect Dis. 2012;18(1):179.
Cajimat MN, Rodriguez SE, Schuster IU, et al. Genomic characterization of Crimean Congo hemorrhagic fever virus in _Hyalomma_ tick from Spain, 2014. Vector Borne Zoonotic Dis. 2017;17(10):714-719.
Negredo A, de la Calle-Prieto F, Palencia-Herrejan E, et al. Autochthonous Crimean Congo hemorrhagic fever in Spain. N Engl J Med. 2017;377(2):154-161.
Pena Estrada A, Bouattour A, Camicas J, Walker A. Ticks of domestic animals in the Mediterranean region: a guide to identification of species. Zaragoza (Spain): University of Zaragoza Press 2004:128.

